#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:634
#, no-c-format
msgid "&libvirt; provides more control over the save and restore operations than &vmm;. <command>virsh save</command> and <command>virsh restore</command> support several options to modify the behavior of the operations. In the most basic form, a &vmguest; is saved by providing its name, ID, or UUID and a file name. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:641
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh save openSUSE-Leap /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:642
#, no-c-format
msgid "A basic &vmguest; restore operation only requires specifying the save file name. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:646
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh restore /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:647
#, no-c-format
msgid "As &vmguest; memory size increases, save and restore operations may require additional options to attain satisfactory transfer rates, particularly when the save image files are backed by high throughput storage. The &vmhost; file system cache is often counterproductive in these scenarios and should be avoided with the <option>bypass-cache</option> option. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:655
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh save --bypass-cache openSUSE-Leap /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:656
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh restore --bypass-cache /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:657
#, no-c-format
msgid "The time required to save and restore &vmguest;s to high throughput storage can be improved by using multiple channels to write and read the &vmguest; memory pages. As noted in <xref linkend=\"sec-libvirt-manage-save\"/> , the <option>sparse</option> image format is required to use multiple channels. When selecting the number of channels, care must be taken to ensure the operation does not adversely affect other workloads running on the &vmhost;. When the &vmhost; resources are statically partitioned, general advice would be to use the same number of channels as physical CPUs dedicated to the &vmguest;. The vCPUs of a &vmguest; are stopped at the start of a save operation, thus it would be safe to use those CPU resources to save &vmguest; memory pages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:671
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following examples save and restore a &vmguest; using 4 channels, while also bypassing the &vmhost; file system cache:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:675
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh save --bypass-cache --image-format sparse --parallel-channels 4 openSUSE-Leap /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: libvirt_managing.xml:676
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;virsh restore --bypass-cache --parallel-channels 4 /virtual/saves/openSUSE-Leap.vmsav"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:677
#, no-c-format
msgid "The image format is encoded in the save image file and does not need to be specified during a restore operation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:681
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information on save/restore and the supported options, see <command>virsh help save</command> , <command>virsh help restore</command> or <command>man 1 virsh</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:689
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating and managing snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:691
#, no-c-format
msgid "&vmguest; snapshots are snapshots of the complete virtual machine including the state of CPU, RAM, devices and the content of all writable disks. To use virtual machine snapshots, all the attached hard disks need to use the qcow2 disk image format, and at least one of them needs to be writable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:699
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots let you restore the state of the machine at a particular point in time. This is useful when undoing a faulty configuration or the installation of a lot of packages. After starting a snapshot that was created while the &vmguest; was shut off, you need to boot it. Any changes written to the disk afterward are lost when starting the snapshot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots are supported on &kvm; &vmhost;s only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: libvirt_managing.xml:715
#, no-c-format
msgid "Terminology"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:716
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are several specific terms used to describe the types of snapshots:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:722
#, no-c-format
msgid "Internal snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:724
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots that are saved into the qcow2 file of the original &vmguest;. The file holds both the saved state of the snapshot and the changes made since the snapshot was taken. The main advantage of internal snapshots is that they are all stored in one file and therefore it is easy to copy or move them across multiple machines."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:735
#, no-c-format
msgid "External snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:737
#, no-c-format
msgid "When creating an external snapshot, the original qcow2 file is saved and made read-only, while a new qcow2 file is created to hold the changes. The original file is sometimes called a <emphasis>backing</emphasis> or <emphasis>base</emphasis> file, while the new file with all the changes is called an <emphasis>overlay</emphasis> or <emphasis>derived</emphasis> file. External snapshots are useful when performing backups of &vmguest;s. However, external snapshots are not supported by &vmm;, and cannot be deleted by <command>virsh</command> directly. For more information on external snapshots in &qemu;, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha-qemu-guest-inst-qemu-img-effect\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:753
#, no-c-format
msgid "Live snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:755
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots created when the original &vmguest; is running. Internal live snapshots support saving the devices, and memory and disk states, while external live snapshots with <command>virsh</command> support saving either the memory state, or the disk state, or both."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: libvirt_managing.xml:765
#, no-c-format
msgid "Offline snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: libvirt_managing.xml:767
#, no-c-format
msgid "Snapshots created from a &vmguest; that is shut off. This ensures data integrity as all the guest's processes are stopped and no memory is in use."
msgstr ""

